<subSubSection id="C32A655D4D58FF97FF3EF8A8B328C38A" pageId="1" pageNumber="94" type="etymology">
<paragraph id="8B8F36D64D58FF97FF3EF8A8B328C38A" blockId="1.[151,1436,1825,2030]" pageId="1" pageNumber="94">
<emphasis id="B944EAC44D58FF97FF3EF8A8B11FC355" bold="true" box="[199,334,1861,1886]" pageId="1" pageNumber="94">Etymology.</emphasis>
The generic epithet derives from the Greek, 
<emphasis id="B944EAC44D58FF97FCBFF8AAB329C355" box="[838,888,1863,1886]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="94">cera</emphasis>
(horn), and 
<taxonomicName id="4C304D554D58FF97FBFAF8AAB434C355" box="[1027,1125,1863,1886]" class="Insecta" family="Panorpidae" genus="Panorpa" kingdom="Animalia" order="Mecoptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="94" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B944EAC44D58FF97FBFAF8AAB434C355" box="[1027,1125,1863,1886]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="94">Panorpa</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, referring to the single anal horn on tergum VI of males and being closely related to 
<taxonomicName id="4C304D554D58FF97FCE9F887B323C38A" box="[784,882,1898,1921]" class="Insecta" family="Panorpidae" genus="Panorpa" kingdom="Animalia" order="Mecoptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="94" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B944EAC44D58FF97FCE9F887B323C38A" box="[784,882,1898,1921]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="94">Panorpa</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="C32A655D4D58FF94FF3EF860B1C7C516" lastPageId="2" lastPageNumber="95" pageId="1" pageNumber="94" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph id="8B8F36D64D58FF94FF3EF860B1C7C516" blockId="1.[151,1436,1825,2030]" lastBlockId="2.[151,1436,151,285]" lastPageId="2" lastPageNumber="95" pageId="1" pageNumber="94">
<emphasis id="B944EAC44D58FF97FF3EF860B110C3AD" bold="true" box="[199,321,1933,1958]" pageId="1" pageNumber="94">Diagnosis.</emphasis>
<taxonomicName id="4C304D554D58FF97FEB2F863B1B3C3AE" box="[331,482,1934,1957]" class="Insecta" family="Panorpidae" genus="Cerapanorpa" kingdom="Animalia" order="Mecoptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="94" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus" status="gen. nov.">
<emphasis id="B944EAC44D58FF97FEB2F863B1B3C3AE" box="[331,482,1934,1957]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="94">Cerapanorpa</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<emphasis id="B944EAC44D58FF97FE15F860B208C3AD" bold="true" box="[492,601,1933,1958]" pageId="1" pageNumber="94">
<taxonomicNameLabel id="A27757BF4D58FF97FE15F860B208C3AD" box="[492,601,1933,1958]" pageId="1" pageNumber="94" rank="genus">gen. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
</emphasis>
can be distinguished from other genera of 
<taxonomicName id="4C304D554D58FF97FBADF860B483C3AD" box="[1108,1234,1933,1958]" class="Insecta" family="Panorpidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Mecoptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="94" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="family">Panorpidae</taxonomicName>
by the following characters: (1) tergum VI of males with a digitate anal horn; (2) aedeagus with dorsal valves sclerotized and prolonged caudally, ventral valves extremely short and membranous; (3) parameres simple, seldom furcated, bearing spines on apical half; (4) hypandrium (sternum IX) composed of a very short basal stalk and a pair of elongate hypovalves; (5) female genital plate complicated and developed, with a broad main plate, bearing a pair of basal plates each on dorsal and ventral sides and the well-developed elongate rod-like axis prominently extending beyond the main plate.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<caption id="DF4F665E4D5BFF94FF6EF9ECB554C2BB" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/262940/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="95" targetBox="[188,1398,339,1492]" targetPageId="2">
<paragraph id="8B8F36D64D5BFF94FF6EF9ECB554C2BB" blockId="2.[151,1436,1537,1712]" pageId="2" pageNumber="95">
<emphasis id="B944EAC44D5BFF94FF6EF9ECB143C21D" bold="true" box="[151,274,1537,1559]" pageId="2" pageNumber="95">FIGURE 1.</emphasis>
<taxonomicName id="4C304D554D5BFF94FEE1F9EFB1B8C21C" box="[280,489,1537,1559]" class="Insecta" family="Panorpidae" genus="Cerapanorpa" kingdom="Animalia" order="Mecoptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="95" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="obtusa">
<emphasis id="B944EAC44D5BFF94FEE1F9EFB1B8C21C" box="[280,489,1537,1559]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="95">Cerapanorpa obtusa</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. (A) and (B) Male and female habitus, photo by Lu Jiang; (C) notal organ and postnotal organ of male, lateral view; (D) abdominal segments V–IX of male, lateral view (from Ma 
<emphasis id="B944EAC44D5BFF94FC16F9CCB44DC23E" box="[1007,1052,1567,1590]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="95">et al</emphasis>
. 2014); (E) tergum VI of male, dorsal view, showing the anal horn; (F) and (G) genital bulbs, ventral and dorsal views; (H) aedeagus, ventral view; (I) left paramere, ventral view. Abbreviations: Ae, aedeagus; AH, anal horn; BP, basal process; DV, dorsal valve; Ep, epandrium; Gcx, gonocoxite; Gs, gonostylus; Hv, hypovalve; LP, lateral process; MT, median tooth; NO, notal organ; Pm, paramere; PnO, postnotal organ; VV, ventral valve. Scale bars: C, F, G = 0.20 mm, D = 1.00 mm, E = 0.50 mm, H, I = 0.10 mm.
</paragraph>
</caption>
<subSubSection id="C32A655D4D5BFF95FF3EF93AB5CCC613" lastPageId="3" lastPageNumber="96" pageId="2" pageNumber="95" type="description">
<paragraph id="8B8F36D64D5BFF95FF3EF93AB5CCC613" blockId="2.[151,1437,1751,2028]" lastBlockId="3.[151,1437,151,968]" lastPageId="3" lastPageNumber="96" pageId="2" pageNumber="95">
<emphasis id="B944EAC44D5BFF94FF3EF93AB108C2FB" bold="true" box="[199,345,1751,1776]" pageId="2" pageNumber="95">Description.</emphasis>
Head almost uniformly black on frons, vertex and occiput. Rostrum yellowish brown to black anteriorly, relatively paler on lateral sides. Thorax dark black on dorsum, pale yellow on pleura (
<figureCitation id="130B2A534D5BFF94FAF5F916B51EC31F" box="[1292,1359,1787,1812]" captionStart="FIGURE 1" captionStartId="2.[151,250,1537,1559]" captionTargetBox="[188,1398,339,1492]" captionTargetId="figure@2.[188,1398,339,1512]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="FIGURE 1. Cerapanorpa obtusa. (A) and (B) Male and female habitus, photo by Lu Jiang; (C) notal organ and postnotal organ of male, lateral view; (D) abdominal segments V – IX of male, lateral view (from Ma et al. 2014); (E) tergum VI of male, dorsal view, showing the anal horn; (F) and (G) genital bulbs, ventral and dorsal views; (H) aedeagus, ventral view; (I) left paramere, ventral view. Abbreviations: Ae, aedeagus; AH, anal horn; BP, basal process; DV, dorsal valve; Ep, epandrium; Gcx, gonocoxite; Gs, gonostylus; Hv, hypovalve; LP, lateral process; MT, median tooth; NO, notal organ; Pm, paramere; PnO, postnotal organ; VV, ventral valve. Scale bars: C, F, G = 0.20 mm, D = 1.00 mm, E = 0.50 mm, H, I = 0.10 mm." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/262940/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="95">Fig. 1</figureCitation>
A, B). Pronotum with black bristles along its anterior margin. Legs pale yellow, tarsomeres darkening toward the apex. Wing membrane hyaline, often with dark markings, seldom with yellow tinge. Abdominal segments I −VI brownish black on terga, paler on sterna and pleural membrane; segments VII and IX yellowish brown. In males, posterior margin of tergum III slightly produced posteriorly into a flat semicircular notal organ; postnotal organ on tergum IV small and pointed forward (
<figureCitation id="130B2A534D5BFF94FE07F842B211C3C3" box="[510,576,1967,1992]" captionStart="FIGURE 1" captionStartId="2.[151,250,1537,1559]" captionTargetBox="[188,1398,339,1492]" captionTargetId="figure@2.[188,1398,339,1512]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="FIGURE 1. Cerapanorpa obtusa. (A) and (B) Male and female habitus, photo by Lu Jiang; (C) notal organ and postnotal organ of male, lateral view; (D) abdominal segments V – IX of male, lateral view (from Ma et al. 2014); (E) tergum VI of male, dorsal view, showing the anal horn; (F) and (G) genital bulbs, ventral and dorsal views; (H) aedeagus, ventral view; (I) left paramere, ventral view. Abbreviations: Ae, aedeagus; AH, anal horn; BP, basal process; DV, dorsal valve; Ep, epandrium; Gcx, gonocoxite; Gs, gonostylus; Hv, hypovalve; LP, lateral process; MT, median tooth; NO, notal organ; Pm, paramere; PnO, postnotal organ; VV, ventral valve. Scale bars: C, F, G = 0.20 mm, D = 1.00 mm, E = 0.50 mm, H, I = 0.10 mm." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/262940/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="95">Fig. 1</figureCitation>
C); tergum VI with a digitate anal horn on the posterior margin (
<figureCitation id="130B2A534D5BFF94FACBF842B525C3C3" box="[1330,1396,1967,1992]" captionStart="FIGURE 1" captionStartId="2.[151,250,1537,1559]" captionTargetBox="[188,1398,339,1492]" captionTargetId="figure@2.[188,1398,339,1512]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="FIGURE 1. Cerapanorpa obtusa. (A) and (B) Male and female habitus, photo by Lu Jiang; (C) notal organ and postnotal organ of male, lateral view; (D) abdominal segments V – IX of male, lateral view (from Ma et al. 2014); (E) tergum VI of male, dorsal view, showing the anal horn; (F) and (G) genital bulbs, ventral and dorsal views; (H) aedeagus, ventral view; (I) left paramere, ventral view. Abbreviations: Ae, aedeagus; AH, anal horn; BP, basal process; DV, dorsal valve; Ep, epandrium; Gcx, gonocoxite; Gs, gonostylus; Hv, hypovalve; LP, lateral process; MT, median tooth; NO, notal organ; Pm, paramere; PnO, postnotal organ; VV, ventral valve. Scale bars: C, F, G = 0.20 mm, D = 1.00 mm, E = 0.50 mm, H, I = 0.10 mm." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/262940/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="95">Fig. 1</figureCitation>
D); basal half segment VII considerably thinner than apical half, dilated apically; segment VIII as long as segment VII, gradually dilated apically. Genital bulb oval (
<figureCitation id="130B2A534D5AFF95FD68FF7AB29EC4BB" box="[657,719,151,176]" captionStart="FIGURE 1" captionStartId="2.[151,250,1537,1559]" captionTargetBox="[188,1398,339,1492]" captionTargetId="figure@2.[188,1398,339,1512]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="FIGURE 1. Cerapanorpa obtusa. (A) and (B) Male and female habitus, photo by Lu Jiang; (C) notal organ and postnotal organ of male, lateral view; (D) abdominal segments V – IX of male, lateral view (from Ma et al. 2014); (E) tergum VI of male, dorsal view, showing the anal horn; (F) and (G) genital bulbs, ventral and dorsal views; (H) aedeagus, ventral view; (I) left paramere, ventral view. Abbreviations: Ae, aedeagus; AH, anal horn; BP, basal process; DV, dorsal valve; Ep, epandrium; Gcx, gonocoxite; Gs, gonostylus; Hv, hypovalve; LP, lateral process; MT, median tooth; NO, notal organ; Pm, paramere; PnO, postnotal organ; VV, ventral valve. Scale bars: C, F, G = 0.20 mm, D = 1.00 mm, E = 0.50 mm, H, I = 0.10 mm." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/262940/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="96">Fig. 1</figureCitation>
F, G); epandrium (tergum IX) slightly tapering toward the apex, with a shallow to deep U-shaped terminal emargination; hypovalves elongate, with the medial margin bearing stout bristles; gonocoxite usually with a group of black setae on the meso-apex, and a small subapical tooth on medial margin; gonostylus shorter than gonocoxite, medially curved, ending in an acute apex, with a flat cup-like basal process and a small mesal tooth on inner margin (
<figureCitation id="130B2A534D5AFF95FD46FECAB2AFC54B" box="[703,766,295,320]" captionStart="FIGURE 1" captionStartId="2.[151,250,1537,1559]" captionTargetBox="[188,1398,339,1492]" captionTargetId="figure@2.[188,1398,339,1512]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="FIGURE 1. Cerapanorpa obtusa. (A) and (B) Male and female habitus, photo by Lu Jiang; (C) notal organ and postnotal organ of male, lateral view; (D) abdominal segments V – IX of male, lateral view (from Ma et al. 2014); (E) tergum VI of male, dorsal view, showing the anal horn; (F) and (G) genital bulbs, ventral and dorsal views; (H) aedeagus, ventral view; (I) left paramere, ventral view. Abbreviations: Ae, aedeagus; AH, anal horn; BP, basal process; DV, dorsal valve; Ep, epandrium; Gcx, gonocoxite; Gs, gonostylus; Hv, hypovalve; LP, lateral process; MT, median tooth; NO, notal organ; Pm, paramere; PnO, postnotal organ; VV, ventral valve. Scale bars: C, F, G = 0.20 mm, D = 1.00 mm, E = 0.50 mm, H, I = 0.10 mm." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/262940/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="96">Fig. 1</figureCitation>
F); parameres sclerotized, simple or seldom furcate, usually bearing spines apically (
<figureCitation id="130B2A534D5AFF95FE57FEA1B1A0C56F" box="[430,497,332,357]" captionStart="FIGURE 1" captionStartId="2.[151,250,1537,1559]" captionTargetBox="[188,1398,339,1492]" captionTargetId="figure@2.[188,1398,339,1512]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="FIGURE 1. Cerapanorpa obtusa. (A) and (B) Male and female habitus, photo by Lu Jiang; (C) notal organ and postnotal organ of male, lateral view; (D) abdominal segments V – IX of male, lateral view (from Ma et al. 2014); (E) tergum VI of male, dorsal view, showing the anal horn; (F) and (G) genital bulbs, ventral and dorsal views; (H) aedeagus, ventral view; (I) left paramere, ventral view. Abbreviations: Ae, aedeagus; AH, anal horn; BP, basal process; DV, dorsal valve; Ep, epandrium; Gcx, gonocoxite; Gs, gonostylus; Hv, hypovalve; LP, lateral process; MT, median tooth; NO, notal organ; Pm, paramere; PnO, postnotal organ; VV, ventral valve. Scale bars: C, F, G = 0.20 mm, D = 1.00 mm, E = 0.50 mm, H, I = 0.10 mm." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/262940/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="96">
Fig. 
<date id="FF8E10164D5AFF95FE1CFEA1B1A0C56F" box="[485,497,332,356]" pageId="3" pageNumber="96">1</date>
</figureCitation>
I); aedeagus with a pair of elongated dorsal valves, a pair of membranous ventral valves, and a prominent lateral process (
<figureCitation id="130B2A534D5AFF95FDA6FE82B2CEC583" box="[607,671,367,392]" captionStart="FIGURE 1" captionStartId="2.[151,250,1537,1559]" captionTargetBox="[188,1398,339,1492]" captionTargetId="figure@2.[188,1398,339,1512]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="FIGURE 1. Cerapanorpa obtusa. (A) and (B) Male and female habitus, photo by Lu Jiang; (C) notal organ and postnotal organ of male, lateral view; (D) abdominal segments V – IX of male, lateral view (from Ma et al. 2014); (E) tergum VI of male, dorsal view, showing the anal horn; (F) and (G) genital bulbs, ventral and dorsal views; (H) aedeagus, ventral view; (I) left paramere, ventral view. Abbreviations: Ae, aedeagus; AH, anal horn; BP, basal process; DV, dorsal valve; Ep, epandrium; Gcx, gonocoxite; Gs, gonostylus; Hv, hypovalve; LP, lateral process; MT, median tooth; NO, notal organ; Pm, paramere; PnO, postnotal organ; VV, ventral valve. Scale bars: C, F, G = 0.20 mm, D = 1.00 mm, E = 0.50 mm, H, I = 0.10 mm." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/262940/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="96">Fig. 1</figureCitation>
H). In females, subgenital plate lingulate, widest at middle, bearing long setae along outer margins (
<figureCitation id="130B2A534D5AFF95FDE7FE79B239C5A7" box="[542,616,404,429]" captionStart="FIGURE 2" captionStartId="3.[151,250,1902,1924]" captionTargetBox="[188,1384,1042,1870]" captionTargetId="figure@3.[188,1398,1021,1881]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="FIGURE 2. Female of Cerapanorpa obtusa. (A) and (B) Abdominal segments VIII – XI, lateral and ventral views; (C) subgenital plate, ventral view; (D) – (F) genital plate, ventral, lateral and dorsal views (D from Ma et al. 2014). Abbreviations: Ax, axis; DBP, dorsal basal plate; MP, main plate; PA, posterior arm; VBP, ventral basal plate. Scale bars: A, B, E = 0.20 mm, C = 0.10 mm, D, F = 0.25 mm." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/262941/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="96">Fig. 2</figureCitation>
C); genital plate consisting of a broad main plate with two pairs of membranous basal plates on its dorsal and ventral sides and an elongate median axis (
<figureCitation id="130B2A534D5AFF95FB92FE5AB4FEC5DB" box="[1131,1199,439,464]" captionStart="FIGURE 2" captionStartId="3.[151,250,1902,1924]" captionTargetBox="[188,1384,1042,1870]" captionTargetId="figure@3.[188,1398,1021,1881]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="FIGURE 2. Female of Cerapanorpa obtusa. (A) and (B) Abdominal segments VIII – XI, lateral and ventral views; (C) subgenital plate, ventral view; (D) – (F) genital plate, ventral, lateral and dorsal views (D from Ma et al. 2014). Abbreviations: Ax, axis; DBP, dorsal basal plate; MP, main plate; PA, posterior arm; VBP, ventral basal plate. Scale bars: A, B, E = 0.20 mm, C = 0.10 mm, D, F = 0.25 mm." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/262941/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="96">Fig. 2</figureCitation>
D–F); posterior arms weakly sclerotized; ventral basal plates fused mesally; dorsal basal plates relatively smaller and separated; the rodlike axis elongate and curved dorsad, prominently protruding beyond the main plate and bifurcated in anterior half.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="C32A655D4D5AFF95FF3EFDC9B48EC636" box="[199,1247,548,573]" pageId="3" pageNumber="96" type="distribution">
<paragraph id="8B8F36D64D5AFF95FF3EFDC9B48EC636" blockId="3.[151,1437,151,968]" box="[199,1247,548,573]" pageId="3" pageNumber="96">
